Title: Frankenstein
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Mary Shelley's novel (1818, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026

====

FADE IN:

EXT. ARCTIC ICE FIELD - DAY

An endless white expanse. A ship, frozen in pack ice, sits motionless. CAPTAIN ROBERT WALTON scans the horizon through a spyglass and spots a distant, gaunt figure staggering across the ice toward them.

CUT TO:

INT. WALTON'S SHIP - CABIN - NIGHT

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN (30s, hollow-eyed, feverish) lies wrapped in blankets, barely alive. Walton tends to him.

CAPTAIN WALTON
You've suffered greatly, sir. What could bring a man alone onto the ice?

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
(weak, haunted)
I seek one who fled me. I will not rest until he or I perish.

He begins his account, and the film DISSOLVES into memory.

DISSOLVE TO:

INT. UNIVERSITY OF INGOLSTADT - LABORATORY - NIGHT (MEMORY)

A younger Victor, wild-eyed with obsession, surrounded by anatomical charts, jars, and crude electrical apparatus. Thunder rattles the windows.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN (V.O.)
I had worked hard for nearly two years, for the sole purpose of infusing life into an inanimate body. I did not sleep. I scarcely allowed myself rest.

On a table beneath a sheet lies a large, still shape, stitched together from salvaged parts.

Victor connects a final cable. Lightning flashes through the window. The apparatus SPARKS and HUMS.

A large hand, yellowed and scarred, TWITCHES beneath the sheet.

Victor recoils in horror as the CREATURE sits upright -- enormous, watery-eyed, its expression almost gentle, almost curious.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN (CONT'D)
(recoiling, breathless)
Oh God -- what have I done?

He flees the laboratory, abandoning his creation entirely.

CUT TO:

EXT. INGOLSTADT STREET - NIGHT (CONTINUOUS)

Victor stumbles through the rain, physically ill with dread. He returns at dawn -- the Creature is gone.

CUT TO:

EXT. SWISS ALPS - MER DE GLACE - DAY (MEMORY, LATER)

Victor, grieving after the murder of his young brother William, wanders alone among the glaciers. A massive figure descends toward him across the ice with unnatural speed and agility.

It is the CREATURE -- more collected now, though still monstrous. Victor draws back, disgusted.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
Devil! Do you dare approach me?

THE CREATURE
(measured, wounded)
I expected this reception. All men hate the wretched. How much more do I, the wretchedest of all, deserve your hatred.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
You are my enemy! Begone, vile insect!

THE CREATURE
(fierce, then pleading)
I was benevolent and good; misery made me a fiend. Make me happy, and I shall again be virtuous.

He insists Victor hear his story before judging him further. Reluctantly, Victor sits.

DISSOLVE TO:

EXT. FOREST OUTSIDE THE DE LACEY COTTAGE - VARIOUS (CREATURE'S MEMORY)

The Creature, newly created and alone, learns to survive in the wilderness. He watches, hidden, through a chink in a cottage wall as the blind OLD DE LACEY and his children, FELIX and AGATHA, live in poverty but deep affection.

THE CREATURE (V.O.)
I saw and heard of none like me. Was I, then, a monster, a blot upon the earth, from which all men fled and whom all men disowned?

He learns their language in secret, and comes to love them without their knowledge, leaving firewood at their door each night, unseen.

One day, believing himself ready, the Creature enters and speaks gently with blind Old De Lacey alone.

THE CREATURE
I am full of fears, for if I fail there, I am an outcast in the world forever.

OLD DE LACEY
(kindly, sightless)
To be friendless is indeed to be unfortunate, but the hearts of men, when unprejudiced by any obvious self-interest, are full of brotherly love.

Felix, Agatha, and SAFIE return unexpectedly. Seeing the Creature's monstrous form, Agatha faints, Safie flees, and Felix beats him savagely with a stick, driving him from the only companionship he had ever known.

THE CREATURE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
(over the beating)
From that moment I declared everlasting war against the species, and, more than all, against him who had formed me.

CUT TO:

EXT. SWISS ALPS - MER DE GLACE - DAY (PRESENT, RESUMING)

The Creature finishes his account. Victor, torn between horror and pity, listens in silence.

THE CREATURE
I demand a creature of another sex, but as hideous as myself. Grant this, and we will quit the neighborhood of man forever.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
(after a long pause, sick with dread)
I will do this -- on the condition that you leave Europe forever, and all places in the neighborhood of man.

The Creature agrees and vanishes back across the ice.

CUT TO:

EXT. ORKNEY ISLANDS - DESOLATE HUT - NIGHT (LATER)

Victor works again by candlelight on a second, female creature, sick with revulsion at his own labor. Through the window, the original Creature watches, grinning with anticipation.

Victor suddenly stops, imagining the horror of two such beings breeding a new race. In a fury of resolve, he TEARS the unfinished body apart before the Creature's eyes.

The Creature SCREAMS in rage and grief outside the window.

THE CREATURE
(through the glass, seething)
You can blast my other passions, but revenge remains -- revenge, henceforth dearer than light or food! I shall be with you on your wedding-night!

He vanishes into the dark.

CUT TO:

INT. FRANKENSTEIN HOUSE - GENEVA - NIGHT (WEDDING NIGHT, LATER)

Victor, newly married to ELIZABETH LAVENZA, arms himself and paces the house, believing the threat is against his own life. He steps outside to search the grounds --

A single, terrible SCREAM from within.

He rushes back to find Elizabeth dead on the bed, strangled, in the same manner as his brother and his friend Clerval before her.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
(collapsing, broken)
Everywhere I turn I see the same figure -- his eyes, his jaw, his ghastly grin.

Through the window, the Creature's face appears for a moment in the darkness -- then is gone.

CUT TO:

EXT. ARCTIC ICE FIELD - DAY (PRESENT, RESUMING)

Victor finishes his tale to Walton, exhausted, near death.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
I have pursued him ever since across the world, sustained only by the vow of vengeance I carry in my heart.

CAPTAIN WALTON
(quietly)
Rest now.

VICTOR FRANKENSTEIN
(weakening)
Seek happiness in tranquility, and avoid ambition -- even if it be only the apparently innocent one of distinguishing yourself in science and discoveries.

His breathing slows. Victor Frankenstein dies.

CUT TO:

INT. WALTON'S SHIP - CABIN - NIGHT (LATER)

Walton grieves over the body. A sound at the window -- the CREATURE looms there, vast and terrible, weeping over his creator's corpse.

CAPTAIN WALTON
(stunned, half in dread)
Your repentance is now superfluous. If you had listened to the voice of conscience, Frankenstein would yet have lived.

THE CREATURE
(broken, mournful)
Once, my fancy was full of pleasant visions of virtue, fame, and enjoyment. Now, I am quite alone. He, who created me, is dead -- and when I shall be no more, the very remembrance of us both will speedily vanish.

He speaks of the years of suffering that drove him to become the thing Victor feared -- and of a grief now heavier than his rage.

THE CREATURE (CONT'D)
(quiet, resolved)
I shall collect my funeral pile and consume this miserable frame, that its remains may afford no light to any curious and unhallowed wretch who would create such another as I have been.

He leaps from the cabin window onto an ice raft and is borne away into the darkness, "lost in darkness and distance," never to be seen again.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
